---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>In March 2026, Donald Knuth posed the Directed Hamiltonian Torus Decomposition
problem: partition the arcs of a 3D torus into three directed Hamiltonian
cycles. Claude found a construction for odd <em>m</em>, and Aquino-Michaels
solved even <em>m</em> ≥ 8. The small even cases — <em>m</em>=4 and
<em>m</em>=6 — fell outside those constructions and remained open.</p>

<p>We closed both. The witnesses are formally verified inside the Lean 4 kernel.
This post covers the engineering side — the paper covers the
<a href="/paper/torus_decomposition.pdf">math</a>.</p>

<h2>The Search Problem</h2>

<p>At each of the <em>m</em>³ vertices, three outgoing arcs are assigned to three
colors. There are 3! = 6 valid assignments per vertex. After fixing the origin
to break symmetry, the search space for <em>m</em>=6 is 6<sup>215</sup> ≈ 10<sup>167</sup>
states. Exhaustive enumeration is not an option.</p>

<p>We used Simulated Annealing with a single-vertex mutation operator: pick a
random vertex, change its permutation to one of the five alternatives, accept
or reject via the Metropolis criterion.</p>

<h2>The Energy Function Bug</h2>

<p>The first version of our energy function counted the number of directed
cycles per color. A "good" state would have exactly one cycle per color
(the Hamiltonian cycle). This seems correct, but it has a subtle failure
mode: a functional graph with out-degree 1 can have components that are
directed cycles with trees feeding into them. Our naive cycle count
assigned <em>E</em> = 0 to non-Hamiltonian topologies.</p>

<p>The fix: count weakly connected components <em>and</em> vertices with
in-degree ≠ 1. Only a single Hamiltonian cycle has both one component
and uniform in-degree across all vertices.</p>

<h2>The 12× Speedup</h2>

<p>For <em>m</em>=4 (64 vertices), the baseline engine — which recomputes the
full energy from scratch on every mutation — solved the problem in 93 seconds.
For <em>m</em>=6 (216 vertices), this approach was too slow. Each energy
evaluation touched all 216 vertices across three color subgraphs.</p>

<p>The incremental engine changed a single vertex's permutation, updated
the in-degree counts in O(1), and recounted cycles only for the affected
colors. Rejected mutations were rolled back in place. This gave roughly
12× higher throughput on <em>m</em>=6.</p>

<p>To validate correctness, we ran a 300,000-step fuzz test asserting exact
agreement between the incremental and full-recalculation engines at every
mutation. Zero discrepancies.</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Case</th><th>Engine</th><th>Time</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><em>m</em>=4</td><td>Baseline</td><td>93 s</td></tr>
<tr><td><em>m</em>=4</td><td>Incremental</td><td>3.1 s</td></tr>
<tr><td><em>m</em>=6</td><td>Incremental</td><td>99.5 s</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>Same algorithm, same hyperparameters (α = 0.999998, reheat to
<em>E</em><sup>2/5</sup> on stagnation). The only difference was
per-iteration throughput.</p>

<h2>Cooling Schedule</h2>

<p>Standard exponential cooling stalls on this problem. The energy landscape
has deep local minima — states where two colors form Hamiltonian cycles but
the third fragments into many components. A monotonic schedule gets trapped.</p>

<p>We used non-monotonic cooling: when the best energy stagnates for <em>W</em>
iterations, reset the temperature to max(1, <em>E</em><sub>best</sub><sup>2/5</sup>)
and double the stagnation window. The reheat is proportional to the current
best energy — gentle near the goal, aggressive when far away. Upon improvement,
the window resets.</p>

<p>This schedule was not tuned per problem size. The same parameters
(T₀ = 50, α = 0.999998, E<sup>2/5</sup> reheat) solved both
<em>m</em>=4 and <em>m</em>=6 without modification.</p>

<h2>Lean 4 Verification</h2>

<p>The solver produces a witness: a 216-element array of integers 0–5.
The formal verification is completely independent of the search — it only
takes the witness as input and proves it's valid.</p>

<p>Each proof verifies 15 sub-theorems using Lean's <code>decide</code> tactic:</p>

<ul>
  <li>3 edge-validity checks (each successor lands on a valid torus neighbor)</li>
  <li>3 disjointness checks (no two colors share an arc at any vertex)</li>
  <li>3 injectivity checks (216² = 46,656 pairwise comparisons each)</li>
  <li>3 orbit-length checks (the cycle visits all 216 vertices)</li>
  <li>3 no-short-orbit checks (no sub-tour closes early)</li>
</ul>

<p>The <em>m</em>=6 proof required setting <code>maxHeartbeats</code> to
4 × 10<sup>8</sup> — roughly 100× the default — because the kernel
evaluates every comparison by reduction. It compiles in 57 seconds on an M4.</p>

<h2>What We Learned</h2>

<p><strong>Energy function design matters more than schedule tuning.</strong>
Fixing the energy function (adding in-degree checking) was the difference
between the search converging and not converging. The cooling schedule was
the same across both problem sizes.</p>

<p><strong>Incremental evaluation is the scaling lever.</strong> The
algorithmic improvement (12× throughput) was worth more than any
hyperparameter change. For <em>m</em>=6, the baseline engine likely
would have needed hours.</p>

<p><strong>Formal verification is surprisingly tractable.</strong>
The Lean 4 kernel checked 46,656 pairwise injectivity comparisons
per color in under a minute, with no Mathlib dependencies and no
boolean reflection tricks. The <code>decide</code> tactic handled
everything.</p>

<p><strong>The search and proof are independent artifacts.</strong>
The solver can be wrong, buggy, or nondeterministic. The Lean kernel
doesn't care — it only checks the witness. This separation is the
entire point of formal verification.</p>

<hr>

<p><em>The full paper is available as a
<a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/blob/main/paper/torus_decomposition.pdf">PDF</a>,
and the Lean 4 proofs are in the
<a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/tree/main/src/lean">repository</a>.</em></p>
`;
